@NODE Requirements "ForceMode Documentation - System requirements"

@{b}System Requirements@{ub}

ForceMode needs OS 3.0 or later and MUI version 2.1 or later. I have written
and  tested  it  on an Amiga 1200 with 2 megs of RAM and a 40 meg hard disk,
but it should run well on a 68000 system with less memory and no  hard  disk
(Although this could be a little tricky with MUI).
@ENDNODE

@NODE Workbench "ForceMode Documentation - Workbench startup"

@{b}Workbench startup@{ub}

To start ForceMode from Workbench, simply double  click  on  its  icon.  The
following Tooltypes can be set (Workbench menu item 'Icon/Information...'):

 
 ∑ CX_POPUP=(YES or NO)       Decides whether  ForceMode opens  up the Prefs
                              window at startup  ('YES')  or stays iconified
                              ('NO').
                              Default is 'YES'.
                              
 ∑ SETTINGS=(filename)        Defines the file which ForceMode loads its set-
                              tings from and saves them to.
                              Default is 'ENV:ForceMode.prefs'.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Shell "ForceMode Documentation - Shell startup"

@{b}Shell startup@{ub}

Template:

 ForceMode CX_POPUP/K,SETTINGS/K


 ∑ CX_POPUP=(YES or NO)       Decides whether  ForceMode opens  up the Prefs
                              window at startup  ('YES')  or stays iconified
                              ('NO').
                              Default is 'YES'.
                              
 ∑ SETTINGS=(filename)        Defines the file which ForceMode loads its set-
                              tings from and saves them to.
                              Default is 'ENV:ForceMode.prefs'.



ForceMode doesn't run in the background automatically, you have to start  it
using  "Run  <NIL:  >NIL:"  to  do  this.  If  you  haven't done so, you can
interrupt ForceMode by pressing 'control c'.
@ENDNODE

