@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_Screenmodes "ForceMode Documentation - Screenmode gadgets"

@{b}Screenmode gadgets@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcuts: m,w)

Select any screenmode you would  like  to  be  replaced  in  the  "Available
screenmodes:"  gadget,  then  select  the screenmode you would like it to be
replaced by in the "Replace with:" gadget. Et voilý. Try starting a  program
which attempts to  open a screen with  the screenmode you  have just decided
to be replaced (Make sure the @{" Patch active " link CH_Patch} gadget is checked).

To undo a screenmode replacement, select the same screenmode  first  in  the
"Available  screenmodes:" gadget and then in the "Replace with:" gadget. The
screenmode will now be replaced by itself, which simply means that it  won't
be replaced at all.
@ENDNODE

@NODE LV_Tasks "ForceMode Documentation - Excluded tasks:"

@{b}Excluded tasks@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: t)

When a program in this list opens a screen, ForceMode will do nothing -  the
screen will open as demanded by the program.  The list can be controlled via
the @{" Add " link BT_Add}, @{" Cancel " link BT_Cancel} and @{" Delete " link BT_Delete} gadgets.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Add "ForceMode Documentation - Add"

@{b}Add@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: a)

Lets ForceMode wait for the next program to open a screen. The program  will
be added to the @{" Excluded tasks: " link LV_Tasks} list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Cancel "ForceMode Documentation - Cancel"

@{b}Cancel@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: c)

Stops ForceMode from waiting for the next program  to  open  a  screen,  the
program won't be added to the @{" Excluded tasks: " link LV_Tasks} list.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Delete "ForceMode Documentation - Delete"

@{b}Delete@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: d)

Removes the selected entry of the @{" Excepted tasks: " link LV_Tasks} list. The program won't
be excluded anymore.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Rescan "ForceMode Documentation - Rescan screenmodes"

@{b}Rescan screenmodes@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: e)

If you have added screenmodes  after starting ForceMode,  use this gadget to
tell ForceMode that there are new screenmodes.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Reset "ForceMode Documentation - Reset screenmodes"

@{b}Reset screenmodes@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: n)

This will undo all your settings,  a safety requester will warn you and give
the opportunity to cancel.
@ENDNODE

@NODE CH_Patch "ForceMode Documentation - Patch active"

@{b}Patch active@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: p)

If this is checked, ForceMode will replace all screenmodes according to your
settings. Otherwise ForceMode will do nothing and all screens will be opened
as  demanded  by  the  program.  ForceMode  patches  the  system   functions
OpenScreen()  and  OpenScreenTagList()  (also OpenScreenTags(), for it calls
OpenScreenTagList()).
@ENDNODE

@NODE CH_Auto "ForceMode Documentation - Set AUTOSCROLL flag"

@{b}Set AUTOSCROLL flag@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: f)

If this is checked and the @{" Patch active " link CH_Patch} gadget is also checked, ForceMode
will set the AUTOSCROLL-flag, which causes screens bigger than  the  display
to  be  scrolled  automatically,  with  EVERY  screen  opened.  This is very
important when replacing screenmodes with smaller ones, for without this you
won't be able to move to the invisible parts of the screen.
@ENDNODE

@NODE RA_Replace "ForceMode Documentation - Replace Screenmode:"

@{b}Replace screenmode@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: r)

This decides how important the settings you made are:


 ∑ Always:             ForceMode  will always  replace every  screenmode you
                       have decided to.  If the new mode is not displayable,
                       the screen will not open and the program will receive
                       an error.

                       ATTENTION!
                       Trying to open a non-displayable screen can cause the
                       machine to crash.  Use this option only if your moni-
                       tor can't display certain screenmodes.


 ∑ Only if             ForceMode will check before replacing a screenmode if
   displayable:        the new one is  displayable with the  demanded number
                       of colors etc.  If it is not, the demanded screenmode
                       will be used.
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Hide "ForceMode Documentation - Hide window"

@{b}Hide window@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: h, right Amiga h)

Iconifies the ForceMode Preferences window.

    @{"How to close and open the Preferences window" link CloseOpen}
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_About "ForceMode Documentation - About..."

@{b}About...@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: b, right Amiga ?)

Pops up an information requester. (Really? Wow...)
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Save "ForceMode Documentation - Save settings"

@{b}Save settings@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: s, right Amiga s)

Saves all  settings to  the  file  specified via  the  SETTINGS  option (see
@{"  Workbench startup  " link Workbench} or @{"  Shell startup  " link Shell} on how to change this - default
is "ENV:ForceMode.prefs").
@ENDNODE

@NODE BT_Quit "ForceMode Documentation - Quit"

@{b}Quit@{ub}    (Keyboard shortcut: q, right Amiga q)

Removes all patches and quits.
@ENDNODE

